1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:06,170
In this video, we are going to learn logical and physical implementation of the secrets.

2
00:00:06,500 --> 00:00:09,920
Secrets can be implemented in two main ways.

3
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:13,190
These are the logical and physical implementation.

4
00:00:13,280 --> 00:00:16,850
Let me start with the logical implementation of secrets.

5
00:00:16,850 --> 00:00:20,180
We will splitting to operations, not databases.

6
00:00:20,180 --> 00:00:27,800
In a logical implementation of secrets, the key idea is separate read and write operations at the code

7
00:00:27,800 --> 00:00:31,310
level, but not necessarily at the database level.

8
00:00:31,310 --> 00:00:38,180
So that means we will separate the query and command operations at the code level and not separate in

9
00:00:38,180 --> 00:00:39,410
the database level.

10
00:00:39,410 --> 00:00:44,750
Both types of the operations still interact with the same underlying database.

11
00:00:45,530 --> 00:00:51,980
So we said that it is the same database but different paths, even though the same database is used.

12
00:00:52,010 --> 00:00:55,460
The path for reading and writing data are distinct.

13
00:00:55,790 --> 00:01:01,700
This means that you might have different models or methods for querying and updating data.

14
00:01:01,700 --> 00:01:08,450
For instance, read operations could utilize the simple data transfer object optimized for performance,

15
00:01:08,450 --> 00:01:14,870
while write operations might interact with a more complex domain model to ensure business rules and

16
00:01:14,870 --> 00:01:16,520
validations are enforced.

17
00:01:17,090 --> 00:01:22,340
So the second type of the implementation is physical implementation of the queries.

18
00:01:22,850 --> 00:01:29,690
A physical implementation of the securities involves splitting the read and write operations, not just

19
00:01:29,690 --> 00:01:34,220
at the code level, but also physically using the separate databases.

20
00:01:34,310 --> 00:01:40,100
This is often seen in a more complex systems, particularly when scaling is a concern.

21
00:01:40,520 --> 00:01:45,590
So there is a synchronization challenge happen when we are separate databases.

22
00:01:45,920 --> 00:01:52,850
While a physical implementation can offer performance advantages and better scaling capabilities, it

23
00:01:52,850 --> 00:02:00,020
also introduces complexity in terms of maintaining data consistency and synchronization between the

24
00:02:00,020 --> 00:02:01,670
read and write operations.

25
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:08,120
So you can see that if we separate the write and read databases, we have to concern about the synchronization

26
00:02:08,120 --> 00:02:08,960
challenges.

27
00:02:09,590 --> 00:02:16,520
That's why logical security is often the first step in adopting this security pattern, especially for

28
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:21,950
applications where the overhead of managing separate databases is not justified.

29
00:02:21,950 --> 00:02:29,120
It offers many of the benefits of the six, such as the clearer separation of concerns and potentially

30
00:02:29,120 --> 00:02:35,990
more optimized read operations, without adding additional complexity of the managing separate databases.

31
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:43,220
For that reason, during the course, we will implement the logical sequence with ASP.Net Core and Mediator.

